1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
https://slama.dev/comeback/

2
00:00:08,050 --> 00:00:08,850
Did you see that?

3
00:00:09,450 --> 00:00:10,850
There was an ambulance here just now.

4
00:00:11,350 --> 00:00:12,650
Yeah, I walked by.

5
00:00:13,150 --> 00:00:14,920
And you won't even tell me what happened to who?

6
00:00:15,050 --> 00:00:17,180
So you'd think, like always, that you're next in line?

7
00:00:17,550 --> 00:00:18,860
You're exaggerating, aren't you?

8
00:00:19,150 --> 00:00:21,640
And what about that time they took that guy downstairs with appendicitis?

9
00:00:21,950 --> 00:00:24,050
But I really did get a stabbing pain in my side.

10
00:00:24,750 --> 00:00:25,410
Sure.

11
00:00:25,850 --> 00:00:26,750
So what happened?

12
00:00:27,250 --> 00:00:28,750
Podroužek had a heart attack.

13
00:00:30,620 --> 00:00:31,100
Podroužek?

14
00:00:32,850 --> 00:00:34,550
He's younger than me.

15
00:00:35,050 --> 00:00:36,650
Don't take it so hard.

16
00:00:37,250 --> 00:00:39,150
I was completely drenched in cold sweat.

17
00:00:43,850 --> 00:00:45,550
My left arm is starting to tingle.

18
00:00:47,250 --> 00:00:48,150
Here we go.

19
00:00:48,450 --> 00:00:51,550
Iva, who's on duty at the clinic today?

20
00:01:31,230 --> 00:01:31,710
Lexa!

21
00:01:38,250 --> 00:01:39,450
I thought we agreed on some secrecy, right?

22
00:01:39,850 --> 00:01:43,250
If you think I'm actually going to call you Mr. Banana, you're mistaken.

23
00:01:43,250 --> 00:01:45,010
Are we doing a secret operation again, or what?

24
00:01:45,450 --> 00:01:47,250
We're not doing a secret operation.

25
00:01:47,450 --> 00:01:49,570
We're going rock climbing with the fourth graders.

26
00:01:49,750 --> 00:01:53,950
And we're only hiding it from Dad and from Saša, so she doesn't blab it to him.

27
00:01:54,550 --> 00:01:57,350
You meant the old tiger and the ginger crow, right?

28
00:01:58,250 --> 00:01:59,250
Well, obviously.

29
00:02:01,850 --> 00:02:04,250
Hey, so where are you going, by bus six or by train?

30
00:02:04,310 --> 00:02:06,330
Everything is encrypted in the dead drop.

31
00:02:06,810 --> 00:02:08,390
In the dead drop?

32
00:02:08,610 --> 00:02:08,830
Yeah.

33
00:02:09,650 --> 00:02:13,150
I tried pneumatic mail first, but that didn't work out.

34
00:02:14,610 --> 00:02:15,710
Just tell me.

35
00:02:15,910 --> 00:02:16,650
Are you crazy?

36
00:02:17,350 --> 00:02:19,700
What if the old tiger is eavesdropping on you?

37
00:02:19,850 --> 00:02:22,440
The old tiger is at the doctor's, telling him he's having a heart attack.

38
00:02:22,850 --> 00:02:24,450
Why would he eavesdrop on me?

39
00:02:26,480 --> 00:02:28,180
Fine, where's the dead drop?

40
00:02:30,850 --> 00:02:31,950
When the time comes, you'll find out.

41
00:02:33,050 --> 00:02:35,250
Iva, I found this in the mailbox.

42
00:02:36,080 --> 00:02:36,560
Damn.

43
00:02:36,950 --> 00:02:37,950
Hi, Lexa.

44
00:02:38,200 --> 00:02:38,840
Hello.

45
00:02:39,650 --> 00:02:52,050
It says on it, top secret, signed Mr. Banana.

46
00:02:53,850 --> 00:02:55,050
Do you know what that's supposed to mean?

47
00:02:55,450 --> 00:02:56,350
I really don't know.

48
00:02:56,750 --> 00:02:59,390
But it's probably some nonsense.

49
00:02:59,950 --> 00:03:02,150
Mm, from some stupid person.

50
00:03:02,500 --> 00:03:03,780
Well, I'd better go.

51
00:03:03,780 --> 00:03:06,850
Probably some kids from the fifth floor mixed up the mailboxes.

52
00:03:07,650 --> 00:03:08,940
Mm, some stupid kids.

53
00:03:09,150 --> 00:03:10,080
Iva, what kind of talk is that?

54
00:03:10,080 --> 00:03:10,540
Bye.

55
00:03:10,900 --> 00:03:11,800
Bye, kid.

56
00:03:17,690 --> 00:03:19,530
So how was it at the clinic anyway?

57
00:03:19,610 --> 00:03:20,790
You were there quite a while?

58
00:03:22,050 --> 00:03:24,940
That slacker Brožek wasn't there either, but Doctor Malík was.

59
00:03:25,450 --> 00:03:27,450
And he actually wants to treat people for real.

60
00:03:28,350 --> 00:03:30,140
Right, he doesn't know you yet.

61
00:03:30,250 --> 00:03:31,750
So he takes you seriously.

62
00:03:32,150 --> 00:03:34,950
Iva, I am not a hypochondriac.

63
00:03:35,250 --> 00:03:37,220
Call Ozzák, I want to tell you my results.

64
00:03:37,220 --> 00:03:37,940
Oh boy.

65
00:03:38,350 --> 00:03:41,050
Ozzák, Dad's back from the clinic.

66
00:03:44,250 --> 00:03:45,390
Will you bring me a picture?

67
00:03:45,650 --> 00:03:47,250
Yeah, sure.

68
00:03:49,820 --> 00:03:50,740
I already have the bear.

69
00:03:52,850 --> 00:03:53,650
Wait, this is serious.

70
00:03:54,710 --> 00:03:55,790
It's always serious.

71
00:03:56,550 --> 00:03:59,250
Ozzák, sit down, and you, Iva, listen.

72
00:04:04,150 --> 00:04:05,950
I might have a heart problem.

73
00:04:06,680 --> 00:04:07,500
For real?

74
00:04:09,950 --> 00:04:12,550
Doctor Malík didn't find anything, but I do have problems.

75
00:04:13,980 --> 00:04:14,580
Uh-huh.

76
00:04:15,350 --> 00:04:16,850
Iva, don't brush it off.

77
00:04:17,450 --> 00:04:19,250
Doctor Malík didn't brush it off either.

78
00:04:19,850 --> 00:04:23,890
He prescribed me a Holter monitor and told me to schedule it for a regular day.

79
00:04:23,890 --> 00:04:24,330
What's that?

80
00:04:25,850 --> 00:04:29,150
A Holter is a little device that I'll have on me at all times.

81
00:04:29,370 --> 00:04:31,750
It will record the activity of my heart.

82
00:04:31,830 --> 00:04:33,330
I don't care about that, what's a regular day?

83
00:04:34,250 --> 00:04:39,490
It's a day when Dad lounges around the house all day and then yells at us in the evening for not doing anything.

84
00:04:39,650 --> 00:04:40,950
Iva, don't upset me.

85
00:04:41,250 --> 00:04:43,600
And this is exactly why I ended up with a Holter.

86
00:04:43,600 --> 00:04:44,580
And what is this Holter thing?

87
00:04:46,450 --> 00:04:49,450
Do you really want me to die like Podroužek?

88
00:04:49,450 --> 00:04:52,150
Podroužek didn't die, he's in the hospital.

89
00:04:52,240 --> 00:04:52,840
How come?

90
00:04:52,840 --> 00:04:55,380
His scouts stopped me and were collecting for him.

91
00:04:55,650 --> 00:04:56,600
They have that motto.

92
00:04:56,850 --> 00:04:58,250
Be prepared.

93
00:04:58,540 --> 00:04:59,020
Right.

94
00:04:59,750 --> 00:05:00,600
What are scouts?

95
00:05:01,050 --> 00:05:03,060
They're those kids who are always hanging around here.

96
00:05:03,060 --> 00:05:04,180
Oh, those ones with colds.

97
00:05:04,580 --> 00:05:06,840
No, they just wear those scarves around their necks.

98
00:05:07,160 --> 00:05:08,880
I didn't have to invite them for hot toddy then.

99
00:05:10,450 --> 00:05:13,230
Ozzák, I'm a sick man.

100
00:05:13,230 --> 00:05:13,910
Sorry then.

101
00:05:14,610 --> 00:05:16,130
And leave those scouts alone.

102
00:05:16,250 --> 00:05:17,770
You know how sensitive Podroužek is about them.

103
00:05:18,050 --> 00:05:19,990
Jesus, Podroužek is in the hospital, isn't he?

104
00:05:20,250 --> 00:05:23,130
And I'll end up there too if you keep stressing me out.

105
00:05:23,370 --> 00:05:25,190
Fine, I'll go so I don't stress you out.

106
00:05:25,310 --> 00:05:25,990
See?

107
00:05:26,090 --> 00:05:26,970
That's exactly it.

108
00:05:27,350 --> 00:05:34,630
And all I want is for us to agree like normal people on when I'll have my regular day.

109
00:05:34,630 --> 00:05:37,270
So just tell us already, damn it, what a regular day is!

110
00:05:37,610 --> 00:05:38,050
A day?

111
00:05:38,650 --> 00:05:40,870
When nothing unusual happens.

112
00:05:40,870 --> 00:05:46,830
So the day we're talking about is a day when there's no risk of anything getting out of hand.

113
00:05:46,830 --> 00:05:47,450
Exactly.

114
00:05:47,630 --> 00:05:47,850
Well!

115
00:05:48,730 --> 00:05:49,590
Then not tomorrow.

116
00:05:51,250 --> 00:05:52,050
What are you planning?

117
00:05:52,750 --> 00:05:53,850
Nothing, but it's Friday.

118
00:05:54,250 --> 00:05:56,720
End of a week full of hard work, you let your guard down.

119
00:05:57,150 --> 00:05:57,750
How about Tuesday?

120
00:05:58,250 --> 00:05:59,650
Why Tuesday?

121
00:06:00,150 --> 00:06:04,750
Tuesday is the start of a week full of hard work, you don't plan anything because the end is nowhere in sight.

122
00:06:05,150 --> 00:06:06,750
What hard work?

123
00:06:07,050 --> 00:06:12,060
You mean how you come to the shop at noon, sleep in the back room all afternoon, and go to the pub in the evening?

124
00:06:12,060 --> 00:06:13,400
If you put it that way.

125
00:06:15,550 --> 00:06:17,420
So you're not planning anything for tomorrow?

126
00:06:17,650 --> 00:06:20,150
We're just going to help Metloš's mom with canning.

127
00:06:20,950 --> 00:06:25,450
And does "helping Metloš's mom with canning" in your slang by any chance mean something that ends with the police?

128
00:06:27,100 --> 00:06:27,780
No way.

129
00:06:28,650 --> 00:06:31,000
Poor Metloš's mom is practically blind.

130
00:06:31,350 --> 00:06:32,880
She nearly canned a cat.

131
00:06:32,880 --> 00:06:33,480
Jesus.

132
00:06:34,750 --> 00:06:37,550
Well if you're just going to can stuff, then I might take the...

133
00:06:37,850 --> 00:06:39,350
Holter already tomorrow.

134
00:06:40,050 --> 00:06:41,440
I want to get it over with too.

135
00:06:41,450 --> 00:06:42,450
Well, okay then.

136
00:06:42,950 --> 00:06:44,150
And a Holter is what?

137
00:06:54,550 --> 00:06:55,940
Good morning, Tomáš.

138
00:06:56,150 --> 00:06:57,950
It's going to be a nice day.

139
00:06:58,350 --> 00:07:00,350
A regular day, Marcelka?

140
00:07:01,050 --> 00:07:03,350
It has to be a regular day.

141
00:07:04,250 --> 00:07:05,520
So you already have it on.

142
00:07:07,550 --> 00:07:15,350
And what can it all do?

143
00:07:16,450 --> 00:07:18,250
It constantly monitors my heart.

144
00:07:18,650 --> 00:07:21,250
And once an hour it measures my blood pressure.

145
00:07:21,850 --> 00:07:23,150
Which is quite funny.

146
00:07:23,740 --> 00:07:24,260
Funny?

147
00:07:24,520 --> 00:07:24,640
Yeah.

148
00:07:25,450 --> 00:07:26,550
No matter what I'm doing.

149
00:07:26,650 --> 00:07:29,690
I have to immediately stop moving and talking.

150
00:07:29,950 --> 00:07:30,950
For a whole minute.

151
00:07:32,450 --> 00:07:36,250
And this morning it happened at the post office, which was hilarious, believe me.

152
00:07:36,750 --> 00:07:38,050
Goodness, they must have stared behind the counter when you just froze and stopped talking.

153
00:07:43,030 --> 00:07:46,610
Well, I was actually still standing in line, so nobody noticed.

154
00:07:47,950 --> 00:07:49,250
But it was hilarious.

155
00:07:49,340 --> 00:07:49,900
I see.

156
00:07:51,350 --> 00:07:57,450
9:40, arrival at work, conversation with subordinate...

157
00:07:57,950 --> 00:07:59,030
No stress.

158
00:07:59,350 --> 00:08:01,930
And you have to write everything down like this?

159
00:08:02,350 --> 00:08:06,550
Well, otherwise Doctor Malík wouldn't know what my heart is reacting to.

160
00:08:06,950 --> 00:08:09,350
I've been writing it down since morning, look.

161
00:08:10,150 --> 00:08:11,650
Oh my.

162
00:08:11,950 --> 00:08:13,830
Woke up, no stress.

163
00:08:14,290 --> 00:08:16,410
Breakfast, mild stress.

164
00:08:16,550 --> 00:08:18,130
Iva didn't buy croissants.

165
00:08:20,350 --> 00:08:22,750
Tram ride to work, more stress.

166
00:08:23,350 --> 00:08:24,030
Ticket inspector.

167
00:08:24,450 --> 00:08:25,250
Oh no.

168
00:08:25,350 --> 00:08:30,950
There was this grumpy old man who wanted me to give up my seat, even though I clearly told him that standing stresses me out.

169
00:08:31,150 --> 00:08:34,750
But you should have seen his face when I showed him this setup.

170
00:08:34,860 --> 00:08:37,160
He only had some ridiculous little alarm clock.

171
00:08:40,410 --> 00:08:40,990
Hey.

172
00:08:42,610 --> 00:08:43,410
Got a minute?

173
00:08:44,090 --> 00:08:44,670
One moment.

174
00:08:45,950 --> 00:08:48,150
9:45.

175
00:08:49,150 --> 00:08:52,450
Arrival of friend for the purpose of conversation.

176
00:08:52,650 --> 00:08:54,050
A private conversation.

177
00:08:55,450 --> 00:08:56,250
Of course.

178
00:08:56,850 --> 00:08:58,550
I'll go make some coffee.

179
00:09:01,450 --> 00:09:02,750
I found this in the gutter.

180
00:09:03,760 --> 00:09:04,280
Where?

181
00:09:04,480 --> 00:09:06,180
In the gutter, stuffed inside.

182
00:09:06,380 --> 00:09:07,760
I was checking if there was a bomb in there.

183
00:09:08,060 --> 00:09:09,250
In the gutter?

184
00:09:09,950 --> 00:09:11,890
After the war, they were painting and found a bomb in a gutter.

185
00:09:12,250 --> 00:09:13,270
I just read about it yesterday.

186
00:09:15,450 --> 00:09:17,330
You keep reading that nonsense about spies.

187
00:09:17,330 --> 00:09:17,730
Nonsense?

188
00:09:18,350 --> 00:09:19,530
Look at this.

189
00:09:20,050 --> 00:09:21,050
It's obviously a cipher.

190
00:09:21,950 --> 00:09:24,250
Jege, dege, mege, bugu, segen.

191
00:09:25,350 --> 00:09:27,250
And this here, Mr. Banana.

192
00:09:27,650 --> 00:09:29,260
Yesterday I had something similar in the mailbox.

193
00:09:29,260 --> 00:09:30,080
It's just gibberish.

194
00:09:30,750 --> 00:09:34,010
That's what you said when that coded message from Ostrava came to our building.

195
00:09:34,350 --> 00:09:36,550
That was just a misdirected postcard.

196
00:09:36,950 --> 00:09:43,350
Right, a postcard arrives saying, Mommy it's nice here, the food is good, in a week a plane with the Polish president will crash, and that seems normal to you.

197
00:09:44,150 --> 00:09:45,450
I think Putin is behind this.

198
00:09:45,550 --> 00:09:49,850
Wait, you're seriously telling me that Putin sent us a postcard?

199
00:09:51,450 --> 00:09:53,800
Not Putin directly, one of his agents.

200
00:09:54,250 --> 00:09:57,950
And not to us, but to the agent who lives in our building.

201
00:09:58,850 --> 00:10:02,150
Right, so we have an agent in our building?

202
00:10:02,550 --> 00:10:04,950
And he puts his messages in the gutter.

203
00:10:06,060 --> 00:10:08,080
Look, Simona, I'm not in the mood for this, okay?

204
00:10:08,080 --> 00:10:12,250
I'm a seriously ill person and I don't want to end up like Podroužek.

205
00:10:14,350 --> 00:10:16,350
Well, he could be the agent.

206
00:10:16,740 --> 00:10:17,160
What?

207
00:10:17,450 --> 00:10:19,050
They poisoned him with plutonium.

208
00:10:20,430 --> 00:10:20,850
God.

209
00:10:26,380 --> 00:10:27,640
I made some for you too.

210
00:10:27,820 --> 00:10:28,480
Oh, thanks.

211
00:10:46,130 --> 00:10:46,550
Iva!

212
00:10:47,030 --> 00:10:47,730
Stop it!

213
00:10:47,890 --> 00:10:49,290
I know perfectly well you were looking.

214
00:10:49,450 --> 00:10:52,070
Well, when you're belaying someone, you have to look at them, right?

215
00:10:52,270 --> 00:10:54,630
It's not that you were looking, it's where you were looking.

216
00:10:54,830 --> 00:10:55,570
That's not true.

217
00:10:56,050 --> 00:10:57,550
And you were drooling while doing it.

218
00:10:57,650 --> 00:10:59,770
I'm allergic to dust, my eyes were watering.

219
00:10:59,770 --> 00:11:01,310
I'm not going to the attic to train with you anymore.

220
00:11:01,570 --> 00:11:02,570
Tomorrow I'm climbing with Tibor.

221
00:11:02,730 --> 00:11:03,730
You can't be serious?

222
00:11:03,850 --> 00:11:05,810
Yeah, he doesn't drool and he has a motorcycle.

223
00:11:06,950 --> 00:11:08,550
So that's all I'm good for, huh?

224
00:11:09,650 --> 00:11:12,060
I organized and kept everything secret.

225
00:11:12,350 --> 00:11:14,750
Then you'll go climbing with Tibor and I'll be stuck with Titanic.

226
00:11:15,350 --> 00:11:16,860
Please, what exactly did you organize?

227
00:11:17,050 --> 00:11:18,650
Well, I handled my sister.

228
00:11:18,920 --> 00:11:20,700
I came up with a brilliant cover story.

229
00:11:20,780 --> 00:11:23,060
Yeah, just as long as it doesn't end up like when we went rafting.

230
00:11:23,650 --> 00:11:24,950
This time she'll really give up.

231
00:11:25,250 --> 00:11:27,250
I told her we'd have to get up at four.

232
00:11:27,350 --> 00:11:29,450
And crawl through mud all day.

233
00:11:29,550 --> 00:11:31,980
Iva, are you really going potato picking?

234
00:11:31,980 --> 00:11:32,740
Can I come with you?

235
00:11:35,050 --> 00:11:36,150
I'm climbing with Tibor.

236
00:11:36,350 --> 00:11:37,150
Banana.

237
00:11:38,450 --> 00:11:39,040
I already got a basket.

238
00:11:39,040 --> 00:11:40,560
And I got one for you too, in case you didn't have one.

239
00:11:55,450 --> 00:11:57,450
Two forty.

240
00:11:58,350 --> 00:11:59,950
Finished cocoa.

241
00:12:01,050 --> 00:12:02,850
Mild stress.

242
00:12:04,250 --> 00:12:05,450
Mild stress?

243
00:12:06,150 --> 00:12:08,450
Doctor Malík told me to cut down on sweets.

244
00:12:09,050 --> 00:12:10,650
Then just write "warm beverage."

245
00:12:15,050 --> 00:12:19,550
Finished warm beverage, no stress.

246
00:12:20,950 --> 00:12:21,950
So far so good.

247
00:12:22,650 --> 00:12:26,950
Ozzák will be here soon and I can get on with my afternoon schedule.

248
00:12:27,750 --> 00:12:30,090
There are still three crates to sort in the back.

249
00:12:30,450 --> 00:12:33,850
Marcelka, I told you it could affect the readings, didn't I?

250
00:12:34,050 --> 00:12:34,850
Of course.

251
00:12:35,050 --> 00:12:35,810
Regular day.

252
00:12:37,450 --> 00:12:50,250
What's going on?

253
00:12:50,850 --> 00:12:51,730
We got there late.

254
00:12:52,050 --> 00:12:53,650
The old lady started canning without us.

255
00:12:53,950 --> 00:12:56,870
Luckily she forgot you're supposed to pour in the brine.

256
00:12:57,150 --> 00:12:59,550
Well do something, or she'll choke.

257
00:13:00,150 --> 00:13:01,650
Couldn't you have broken it?

258
00:13:02,050 --> 00:13:03,650
So the little kitty could cut itself?

259
00:13:04,030 --> 00:13:04,590
Herod.

260
00:13:08,450 --> 00:13:12,270
Kid, get out, the cat will eat.

261
00:13:12,750 --> 00:13:15,290
Take that cat back and get back here immediately.

262
00:13:15,290 --> 00:13:16,210
Your shift is starting.

263
00:13:16,550 --> 00:13:17,710
Bro, I can't yet.

264
00:13:18,050 --> 00:13:23,010
Well, Pytel complained that we help Metloš's mom but nobody helps his mom, so we have to go there too.

265
00:13:23,010 --> 00:13:23,610
Wait a minute.

266
00:13:28,450 --> 00:13:31,950
Bro, at least for a little while.

267
00:13:32,110 --> 00:13:33,710
She already started canning on her own too.

268
00:13:33,970 --> 00:13:35,650
And Pytel is worried about his hamsters.

269
00:13:39,050 --> 00:13:39,850
Can I really?

270
00:13:41,450 --> 00:13:43,250
I think he'll say no.

271
00:13:43,250 --> 00:13:46,150
Tomáš, say something.

272
00:13:47,650 --> 00:13:48,150
Well, sure.

273
00:13:48,750 --> 00:13:50,260
Sure, regular day.

274
00:13:50,650 --> 00:13:53,150
Ozzák does whatever he wants and you just let him.

275
00:13:54,250 --> 00:13:55,510
Just let him go, Tomáš.

276
00:13:55,750 --> 00:13:57,290
Bro has a big heart.

277
00:13:57,650 --> 00:13:58,250
Thanks, bro.

278
00:13:58,350 --> 00:13:58,890
Thanks.

279
00:14:10,250 --> 00:14:11,850
2:45.

280
00:14:13,150 --> 00:14:14,750
Blood pressure measurement.

281
00:14:15,050 --> 00:14:17,250
High stress.

282
00:14:19,740 --> 00:14:22,930
And what's this for?

283
00:14:23,950 --> 00:14:26,450
That's a gauge for measuring potatoes.

284
00:14:26,750 --> 00:14:27,250
Really?

285
00:14:27,950 --> 00:14:29,850
Yeah, whichever one fits through it is too small.

286
00:14:30,850 --> 00:14:32,150
Handy little thing.

287
00:14:32,950 --> 00:14:34,100
Are you taking a map?

288
00:14:34,550 --> 00:14:35,250
What for?

289
00:14:35,650 --> 00:14:36,950
So we don't get lost.

290
00:14:37,750 --> 00:14:38,950
How would we get lost?

291
00:14:39,010 --> 00:14:40,690
Well, like when we went to thin out the beets.

292
00:14:40,690 --> 00:14:45,050
We got lost and then had to ride those dangerous rubber dinghies.

293
00:14:45,450 --> 00:14:46,250
Yeah, right.

294
00:14:46,850 --> 00:14:48,200
It could happen again.

295
00:14:48,450 --> 00:14:49,850
You can still stay home.

296
00:14:50,350 --> 00:14:51,550
I'd rather take the map.

297
00:14:52,480 --> 00:14:56,400
And you're taking this to the field?

298
00:14:57,080 --> 00:14:58,780
Yeah, I'm taking this to the field.

299
00:15:01,950 --> 00:15:02,950
I'm taking rubber boots.

300
00:15:03,210 --> 00:15:03,730
Fine.

301
00:15:04,350 --> 00:15:05,370
I'm going to buy tickets.

302
00:15:05,850 --> 00:15:07,450
I wouldn't trust Banana with that.

303
00:15:08,350 --> 00:15:09,300
I'm going to pack too.

304
00:15:09,850 --> 00:15:11,350
And I'm also taking bananas.

305
00:15:21,350 --> 00:15:22,550
Hi, Tomáš.

306
00:15:22,550 --> 00:15:23,070
Hey.

307
00:15:23,230 --> 00:15:24,310
I'm already getting it ready.

308
00:15:24,490 --> 00:15:26,010
Vermouth on ice as usual.

309
00:15:27,050 --> 00:15:27,820
Why vermouth?

310
00:15:28,050 --> 00:15:30,550
I guess you like it, since you order it every time.

311
00:15:30,750 --> 00:15:33,100
I order wine every time?

312
00:15:33,100 --> 00:15:33,680
What kind?

313
00:15:34,750 --> 00:15:37,240
Well, you always pour me the same boxed garbage.

314
00:15:37,240 --> 00:15:38,000
Good, it's you then.

315
00:15:38,850 --> 00:15:40,250
And who else would it be?

316
00:15:41,450 --> 00:15:43,840
You never know who might walk in looking just like you.

317
00:15:43,840 --> 00:15:44,360
Me?

318
00:15:44,800 --> 00:15:45,620
Or a double.

319
00:15:46,550 --> 00:15:48,140
Then ask for his ID.

320
00:15:48,550 --> 00:15:49,450
I'm not an amateur.

321
00:15:49,650 --> 00:15:53,050
Forged documents, entire fake identities in use since the seventies.

322
00:15:53,500 --> 00:15:55,160
Simona, stop it.

323
00:15:55,260 --> 00:15:57,020
Nothing weird is going on here.

324
00:15:57,160 --> 00:15:57,300
No?

325
00:15:59,350 --> 00:16:01,650
Suspicious people were looking for Ozzák here.

326
00:16:02,150 --> 00:16:03,550
And you think that's strange?

327
00:16:03,730 --> 00:16:05,750
Decent people never come looking for Ozzák.

328
00:16:05,810 --> 00:16:07,450
These ones were disguised as scouts.

329
00:16:08,950 --> 00:16:09,680
As scouts?

330
00:16:09,680 --> 00:16:09,860
Yeah.

331
00:16:10,250 --> 00:16:12,150
Who knows if they weren't the Lilliputians from the Kremlin.

332
00:16:12,920 --> 00:16:13,400
Who?

333
00:16:15,450 --> 00:16:16,650
The Lilliputians from the Kremlin.

334
00:16:16,950 --> 00:16:21,150
An elite Putin unit made up of dwarves, operating disguised as children.

335
00:16:21,580 --> 00:16:22,060
Nonsense!

336
00:16:22,650 --> 00:16:24,560
Those must have been Podroužek's scouts too.

337
00:16:24,560 --> 00:16:24,780
Yeah.

338
00:16:25,450 --> 00:16:28,480
Podroužek's scouts looking for Ozzák, that really puts me at ease.

339
00:16:28,480 --> 00:16:29,580
So what could they want from him?

340
00:16:29,780 --> 00:16:30,280
I don't know.

341
00:16:32,050 --> 00:16:33,750
But they coughed a lot.

342
00:16:34,450 --> 00:16:36,390
I'll probably have to talk to them.

343
00:16:36,390 --> 00:16:36,830
Watch out!

344
00:16:37,750 --> 00:16:39,150
They carry poisoned teddy bears.

345
00:16:41,750 --> 00:16:42,750
Mild stress.

346
00:16:44,150 --> 00:16:45,450
High stress.

347
00:17:01,450 --> 00:17:02,010
Uncle?

348
00:17:03,250 --> 00:17:04,350
Ivuška, you're here already?

349
00:17:05,350 --> 00:17:07,150
Guys, this is Ivuška.

350
00:17:07,160 --> 00:17:07,740
Hello.

351
00:17:08,140 --> 00:17:09,180
What's going on here?

352
00:17:09,340 --> 00:17:11,120
We came to help you with canning.

353
00:17:11,400 --> 00:17:11,960
Me?

354
00:17:13,350 --> 00:17:18,950
When you felt bad that we help Pytel's and Metloš's moms but nobody helps you, so here we are.

355
00:17:19,150 --> 00:17:21,370
So nothing happens to any little animal.

356
00:17:21,370 --> 00:17:21,650
Yeah.

357
00:17:23,450 --> 00:17:24,450
What is he talking about?

358
00:17:26,750 --> 00:17:29,350
I told them you almost canned a dog last time.

359
00:17:29,350 --> 00:17:29,830
Why?

360
00:17:30,250 --> 00:17:31,750
Because you can't see well anymore either.

361
00:17:32,650 --> 00:17:34,050
I'm asking why you told them that?

362
00:17:34,450 --> 00:17:35,840
Well, so they'd come help you.

363
00:17:36,150 --> 00:17:37,060
It's terrible, though.

364
00:17:37,060 --> 00:17:39,300
Everyone's always helping everyone else, but nobody helps you.

365
00:17:39,460 --> 00:17:40,600
But I don't need help.

366
00:17:40,840 --> 00:17:42,240
That doesn't matter, it's the principle.

367
00:17:42,780 --> 00:17:44,280
Guys, Ivuška is very happy.

368
00:17:44,500 --> 00:17:45,580
We're human beings, right?

369
00:17:49,250 --> 00:17:50,200
What about the hamsters?

370
00:17:50,550 --> 00:17:53,950
Yeah, we had to bathe them, they were covered in jam.

371
00:17:54,130 --> 00:17:56,590
Uncle, if Dad shows up now, the Holter will go haywire.

372
00:17:56,820 --> 00:17:57,580
You have to get out.

373
00:17:57,640 --> 00:17:59,500
And your brother has something against canning?

374
00:18:00,080 --> 00:18:01,460
He wanted a regular day.

375
00:18:01,460 --> 00:18:03,740
And it was hard enough to talk them into it.

376
00:18:03,740 --> 00:18:05,620
We've done 300 jars today already.

377
00:18:05,720 --> 00:18:06,740
I don't care, leave now.

378
00:18:09,250 --> 00:18:10,150
Jesus, that's Dad.

379
00:18:10,240 --> 00:18:11,720
He probably forgot his keys again.

380
00:18:11,740 --> 00:18:12,640
Get out immediately.

381
00:18:12,860 --> 00:18:14,560
We're just now sterilizing the rubber rings, Iva.

382
00:18:14,880 --> 00:18:15,400
Go.

383
00:18:16,750 --> 00:18:18,050
You have to be gentle with men.

384
00:18:18,750 --> 00:18:20,750
I'll have to explain it to them somehow.

385
00:18:22,050 --> 00:18:22,750
Go!

386
00:18:24,150 --> 00:18:26,650
Is that you?

387
00:18:42,250 --> 00:18:45,730
Lexa also got me a rope, so if there's fog in the field, we won't get lost.

388
00:18:45,730 --> 00:18:46,810
Jesus, take that away.

389
00:18:47,210 --> 00:18:49,070
But I just can't coil it up.

390
00:18:49,110 --> 00:18:50,870
Then tell Lexa, I don't have time right now.

391
00:18:51,450 --> 00:18:54,150
He went to the attic to practice climbing.

392
00:18:55,850 --> 00:18:58,120
Quick, take it to my room and hide it somewhere.

393
00:18:58,120 --> 00:18:59,500
Dad can't see this.

394
00:19:00,220 --> 00:19:01,860
He doesn't like potatoes.

395
00:19:02,380 --> 00:19:03,540
Don't stress him out, go.

396
00:19:06,450 --> 00:19:10,120
Go, go, go.

397
00:19:10,750 --> 00:19:12,050
What do you want?

398
00:19:21,330 --> 00:19:22,630
Is Brother Ozzák here?

399
00:19:22,930 --> 00:19:23,190
No.

400
00:19:24,330 --> 00:19:24,930
How come?

401
00:19:29,050 --> 00:19:30,850
Boy, you kids look rough.

402
00:19:30,850 --> 00:19:35,340
Ozzák, grab the scouts and your buddies and scram, Dad will be here any minute.

403
00:19:35,340 --> 00:19:36,200
Fine then.

404
00:19:36,240 --> 00:19:37,500
Guys, fresh air.

405
00:19:40,050 --> 00:19:45,550
Well, I see we're going to need some medicine.

406
00:19:51,750 --> 00:19:55,550
Ozzák, come back, hurry.

407
00:20:02,170 --> 00:20:02,630
Parents!

408
00:20:15,950 --> 00:20:18,170
I forgot my keys, have you seen them?

409
00:20:18,850 --> 00:20:19,550
No, not at all.

410
00:20:21,450 --> 00:20:21,950
Iva, what's all this?

411
00:20:24,850 --> 00:20:26,250
Sorry, I'll clean it up right away.

412
00:20:27,550 --> 00:20:29,140
Go over to Simona's in the meantime.

413
00:20:29,450 --> 00:20:30,550
Yeah, that's where I'm headed.

414
00:20:30,750 --> 00:20:34,050
And if she keeps reading those books about agents, I'm not going back.

415
00:20:34,650 --> 00:20:38,250
She actually thinks scouts are after Ozzák.

416
00:20:39,200 --> 00:20:40,140
Well, well.

417
00:20:41,150 --> 00:20:41,980
Is Ozzák in his room?

418
00:20:42,550 --> 00:20:45,250
No, no, no, no, no, nobody's in there.

419
00:20:45,550 --> 00:20:48,140
Don't you want to take a twenty-minute nap while I clean up?

420
00:20:49,650 --> 00:20:55,750
I don't know, Iva, I'm supposed to have a regular day and I only nap in the afternoon on Saturdays.

421
00:20:56,550 --> 00:20:59,350
Well, Malík won't lose his mind over it.

422
00:20:59,900 --> 00:21:00,760
That's true.

423
00:21:01,450 --> 00:21:03,650
But it's been quite a day, you know?

424
00:21:05,950 --> 00:21:07,550
At least I've got everything behind me.

425
00:21:11,550 --> 00:21:12,850
Who is it this time?

426
00:21:16,550 --> 00:21:17,350
Good lord!

427
00:21:17,650 --> 00:21:18,850
Mr. Podroužek!

428
00:21:19,150 --> 00:21:20,950
You didn't expect me.

429
00:21:21,650 --> 00:21:22,650
I would have bet on that.

430
00:21:22,850 --> 00:21:23,950
They released you already?

431
00:21:24,650 --> 00:21:25,650
That's beside the point.

432
00:21:25,800 --> 00:21:26,920
Where are the cubs?

433
00:21:27,060 --> 00:21:27,480
Who?

434
00:21:28,050 --> 00:21:28,860
My scouts.

435
00:21:29,850 --> 00:21:30,750
Not here.

436
00:21:30,880 --> 00:21:32,180
The tracks led me here.

437
00:21:33,950 --> 00:21:35,750
But they're not here, right, Iva?

438
00:21:37,460 --> 00:21:38,140
Well.

439
00:21:38,750 --> 00:21:40,450
A few of them came looking for Ozzák.

440
00:21:41,130 --> 00:21:41,690
What?

441
00:21:48,050 --> 00:21:49,250
My cubs.

442
00:21:49,650 --> 00:21:51,650
We missed you, Brother Scoutmaster.

443
00:21:52,650 --> 00:21:53,850
Got a cough drop?

444
00:21:56,350 --> 00:21:57,290
Let's have some medicine.

445
00:21:57,290 --> 00:21:57,610
Hooray!

446
00:21:59,750 --> 00:22:01,150
How do you explain this?

447
00:22:02,430 --> 00:22:03,750
Banana, Podroužek.

448
00:22:03,750 --> 00:22:08,270
In case you ever try to take my troop away again, I want you to know I have a hatchet at home.

449
00:22:08,270 --> 00:22:08,830
Yes.

450
00:22:10,350 --> 00:22:15,580
And luring children with hamsters is the most pathetic trick I know, you pedophile.

451
00:22:17,150 --> 00:22:17,950
Excuse me, I'm leaving.

452
00:22:35,450 --> 00:22:37,050
What the hell is going on here?

453
00:22:38,250 --> 00:22:39,550
The Lilliputians from the Kremlin are here.

454
00:22:41,080 --> 00:22:41,560
Where?

455
00:22:42,640 --> 00:22:43,640
Stop this immediately.

456
00:22:43,860 --> 00:22:44,720
You don't understand.

457
00:22:44,780 --> 00:22:46,320
Where are the Lilliputians from the Kremlin?

458
00:22:46,360 --> 00:22:48,180
Soon the Hara from Helsinki will show up.

459
00:22:49,260 --> 00:22:50,000
The Hara what?

460
00:22:50,000 --> 00:22:52,950
Those Nordic assassins are from the Moscow-Helsinki axis.

461
00:22:53,120 --> 00:22:53,640
Excuse me.

462
00:22:53,640 --> 00:22:58,150
I just wanted to ask if the cops are gone yet.

463
00:22:58,750 --> 00:23:00,750
The Benga from Baghdad.

464
00:23:00,840 --> 00:23:01,360
Good grief.

465
00:23:02,230 --> 00:23:03,570
Explain to me what's going on here.

466
00:23:03,730 --> 00:23:06,310
Nothing, bro, we're just canning.

467
00:23:06,610 --> 00:23:07,770
Dad, calm down.

468
00:23:07,950 --> 00:23:09,030
The Benga from Baghdad.

469
00:23:09,050 --> 00:23:11,410
They're a commando of suicide bombers.

470
00:23:11,550 --> 00:23:13,470
We have to leave before they show up.

471
00:23:13,650 --> 00:23:14,850
Guys, let's go!

472
00:23:15,050 --> 00:23:16,090
The Benga are on their way!

473
00:23:16,270 --> 00:23:16,870
Bye!

474
00:23:17,590 --> 00:23:18,190
See ya!

475
00:23:18,450 --> 00:23:19,570
Take Pytel's hamsters!

476
00:23:24,950 --> 00:23:26,250
Sit down, bro, calm down.

477
00:23:27,520 --> 00:23:28,280
I'll explain.

478
00:23:28,460 --> 00:23:31,300
We agreed on something.

479
00:23:31,600 --> 00:23:32,180
Jesus, hurry!

480
00:23:32,380 --> 00:23:33,340
We have to go!

481
00:23:34,020 --> 00:23:34,600
Mom!

482
00:23:35,060 --> 00:23:35,660
The little animals!

483
00:23:35,880 --> 00:23:36,480
Quick!

484
00:23:36,980 --> 00:23:37,620
Run!

485
00:23:39,450 --> 00:23:42,900
I just can't take it anymore.

486
00:23:56,250 --> 00:23:56,810
She's got a bomb!

487
00:23:58,050 --> 00:23:58,550
Get down!

488
00:24:08,050 --> 00:24:09,650
This is not a Holter, is it?

489
00:24:17,450 --> 00:24:18,950
Sorry, it was a short circuit.

490
00:24:19,550 --> 00:24:21,850
I don't even know if it'll work now.

491
00:24:21,950 --> 00:24:24,330
I probably shouldn't have cut the blue wire.

492
00:24:24,330 --> 00:24:25,390
No, you definitely shouldn't have.

493
00:24:25,950 --> 00:24:27,530
You always cut the red one.

494
00:24:28,050 --> 00:24:29,550
It was just a short circuit.

495
00:24:30,550 --> 00:24:32,100
It's not about the measurement.

496
00:24:32,650 --> 00:24:35,050
Even a healthy heart couldn't have taken this.

497
00:24:36,050 --> 00:24:37,450
I'll end up like Podroužek.

498
00:24:38,050 --> 00:24:43,950
And all I wanted was for you to behave like human beings for just one single day.

499
00:24:47,350 --> 00:24:47,950
It's working.

500
00:24:49,050 --> 00:24:49,850
So from now on.

501
00:24:50,350 --> 00:24:51,550
No shocks, okay?

502
00:24:56,150 --> 00:24:56,750
Alright then.

503
00:25:27,300 --> 00:25:28,020
Good afternoon.

504
00:25:28,650 --> 00:25:29,650
Mr. Pacovský?

505
00:25:31,550 --> 00:25:33,100
Isn't Doctor Malík here?

506
00:25:33,450 --> 00:25:35,350
I'm Doctor Stejskal, have a seat.

507
00:25:36,550 --> 00:25:39,150
I came to ask about my results.

508
00:25:39,550 --> 00:25:41,430
I'm just looking at them, congratulations.

509
00:25:41,430 --> 00:25:42,450
Your heart is strong as a bell.

510
00:25:44,100 --> 00:25:44,620
Really?

511
00:25:45,950 --> 00:25:47,050
That can't be right.

512
00:25:48,750 --> 00:25:49,400
Why not?

513
00:25:49,550 --> 00:25:52,750
The reading can't be reliable, I had a day full of stress.

514
00:25:53,750 --> 00:25:56,050
Well, all the better that your results came out so well, right?

515
00:25:57,150 --> 00:25:59,250
Didn't I have a cardiac arrest in the evening?

516
00:26:01,220 --> 00:26:02,400
Around six or so.

517
00:26:05,750 --> 00:26:06,950
I don't see anything here.

518
00:26:07,760 --> 00:26:09,180
And where is Doctor Malík?

519
00:26:09,200 --> 00:26:10,340
I'd like to discuss it with him.

520
00:26:10,340 --> 00:26:16,250
Unfortunately, Doctor Malík is in the hospital, but don't worry, nothing serious, just his gallbladder, goodbye.

521
00:26:23,450 --> 00:26:24,250
Are you alright?

522
00:26:24,550 --> 00:26:25,050
We already have a teddy bear.
